    <segment id="1" parent="12" relname="span">It appears to me that everyone is on the same page with the intuitive attribute.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="14" relname="span"> 
Its kind of like knowing how a system will react before you actually get there.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> 
It really makes a user comfortable to be able to think a couple of steps ahead of where the user interface is going--and be correct in one&apos;s thinking.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="11" relname="span"> 

On the other hand, there is probably nothing more frustrating than using an interface that is not intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="8" relname="span"> 
How many times have we wondered, why did they do it that way?</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="13" relname="circumstance"> 
When this happens</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="15" relname="span"> there is no comfort in knowing that an interface works a certain way to meet a stated requirement of some type.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="span"> 
It is my contention that intuitive design for all known user groups be a primary usability goal </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="6" relname="elaboration">
and that it is certainly one of the leading sources of frustration for users in their interaction with user interfaces.</segment>
